<username>Rodney Vallo< /username><Pics>None< /Pics><text>Our 5 year old son has been going here for around 6 months and enjoys it up to this day. Master Kang not only teaches Taekwondo styles but also the discipline that is needed.
He makes his classes fun but at the same time serious enough for them to learn what is needed.

Not only do we like how he teaches the class, we like how he continues to teach kids confidence in themselves. He also teaches the importance of a good attitude/behavior they need to show during class and most importantly when outside of class. Respect is also a main teaching in his class.

At home we always remind our son, when his behavior falters (as normal with kids), if that is in line with Master Kang's teachings, and if it is something Master Kang and we as parents should be expecting. Whenever that happens, our son has been more aware of what is the correct attitude and behavior.

If you read other reviews, you can see it is great for kids in that he has a reward system which the kids love. It helps show progress and makes it fun for the kids to do their best in each class.

The most important facet of all this is it that our son has fun. That is what makes him want to go to as many classes as he can during the week.

For anyone interested, please give the trial period a chance. I believe it may be a very low cost and it will help you make the decision on if you and/or your kid will like it.

In all honesty, one may think that pricing may be high (which I thought at first) but since he has started, we have no regrets. It's worth what our son is learning and the fun he is having. We actually even enrolled him a few months ago in the Black Belt Club where it involves additional classes that provide more training in other aspects of Taekwondo. It costs a little more but our son really enjoys going to class. Master Kang does expect a little more from his students in those classes which is understood.<//text>< response>

<Text>My child has been attending Master Kang's school just shy of six months and loves it. My child is an active kid, talks a lot, has attention issues and this program has really helped with a lot of behavioral hurdles that we have faced in the past year. Kang's Sunrise Taekwondo in three words:  Respect, discipline, and fun!

Master Kang has a knack for making his classes fun for the younger kids (my own included). He is steadfast, yet fun and playful, but most definitely knows when to lay down the hammer when need be. All of the children that I have seen attend his class adore him, but most importantly - they respect him as well.

Part of the curriculum that I enjoy as a parent is that each student is held accountable for their behavior at school, at home, and at the studio. Master Kang is very diligent about checking with each parent /guardian on how his students are doing in the other areas of their lives. I personally have no problems tattle telling on my child if she's been disrespectful at home or getting in trouble in school. Master Kang has addresses issues using firm warnings with my own child and takes appropriate steps to keep the children accountable. He also uses praise and uses a color belt stripe system as a check up on progress of each student. Good behavior awards stripes on belts to acknowledge good behavior, all of which are viewable to other students, so it's very public who is and who is not doing well.

The proof that I know that my daughter loves it is she is always excited to come to class, her self esteem has improved, has made friends and likes Master Kang. He aims to help his students build leadership skills and definitely has a firm hand while conducting classes, but he still knows how to motivate and have fun. I have nothing but praise for this school and Master Kang and have spoken to other parents, and who agree and have the same outlook.

Highly recommend attending this school!</Text>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

<resp>None</resp><Rate>5</Rate><pictures>None</pictures>< review>
One of the great by the slice places in the Castro. It's on 18th St. The entrance is small so you could miss it if you're not careful (or intoxicated :) )  Pro Tip: Always ask what's the next pie coming out. And then order a slice from that pie.

I really like being able to see what pizzas they have ready and then getting a quick slice. Sometimes the music's a little too loud, but hey, I guess that's how they keep the employees energized.

Pizza's a little thinner than the other nizario's, but it's still good.< /review>

< Name>
Anatoly Petkov<//Name>

1473016605133</Time>
<rating>4< /rating><Text>A wholly enjoyable experience indeed. The restaurant takes reservations, so we were immediately seated upon arrival and offered drinks. As we hesitated between 2 wines, they let us try both and make an informed choice; one rarely gets that in a restaurant of this price range. We ended up picking Lodi Cabernet, which everyone enjoyed.
The starters were crab cake and watermelon salad. Crab cake was quite and it was served on a bed of what seems to be a mixture of strained yogurt and feta - an unusual combination but not at all bad. The watermelon salad also had lightly pickled radishes, some greens and was topped with farmer's cheese, which was a bit too salty. What I most liked about this salad was the roasted almond tasting, pesto-like paste on the bottom, which turned out to be toasted pistachios with herbs.
Main courses were as follows:
*In-house made gnocchi with some herbs, Brussels Sprouts and more farmer's cheese - a good choice but again a bit saltier that it could have been. *Seared scallops, which were just OK. Usually those tend to be overdone but in this case they were a bit under, yet not as tender as they should be.
*Beef cheek - Yummy! Very well prepared, balanced sauce, seasoned to perfection and served with some mashed taters - hit the spot!
Desserts were good - apple pie with ice cream (made at premises), an interesting interpretation of mud pie, with some coffee flavored ice cream and last, berries with pistachio ice cream which I think was the best choice.
The ambiance was relaxed and many of the people seemed to be repeat customers, which says a lot about a place. Staff were very helpful and informed and ingredients fresh and inventively used.
We all really enjoyed the experience and would definitely like to come back and try more of the chef's creations.</Text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOY0b9K-0E7z42xHU7aM4kp72_J1vzhMPfeZa4Y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN9yGCuXELDg9drE_xmzOlnIZXXde0veUZoKVrc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOHvJBIqFJ0BDflGoZinKdYq4BMiIhqaACB57iT=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM8NRLjTnu1SivUARV_TnuPFkT5z41mQzxs3g1a=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP78L0e4chilwVwJ7HVw8UxSQc5nr9Xblkn_92I=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNHydfYE6bNMkWEV5l7sOcm1wmrJDoPc-iyTNVk=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMmGBWVwGHMmIxRQHZOV51HjbyX4Tq4Abhz_hjM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPgB_Uk9JahEqgUIxI74IYk-pyaSHRMAJ9Qmifz=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOreCvrBajzCQRJ9huZmmREXaC4qJLQPRNhfzCH=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM5JL4LJElKgB3E9iy3n6ZLKCTkSF2Iad2L19ra=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMbxQUWd8vxFbTXtfNclKIxkLoJhdRcirT6vX-W=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMo1YUk_qCjgMrGA5fbovDROhmR__cCrWS7AAuO=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pictures><resp>None<//resp><GmapID>0x80d9551da49011df:0xfd9929fc5837b435<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>

Jorgeanne Cabuhat</username>
<Date>1432221302672</Date><rating>5</rating>< Review>
Came here for dinner to catch up with some friends and it was the perfect location. That night the restaurant was not busy so we lucked out with a cozy table/booth. The restaurant was dimly lit but not too dark that you can't see your food. And the service was nice. As this place uses local produce the menu changes.  At this visit, we ordered the pork belly appetizer, a fried chicken salad, a jidori chicken, and steak and potatoes. Each tasted delicious and were a very generous portion. The steak was cooked perfectly at a medium rare and the potatoes were flavorful and not dense. The pork belly by far was my favorite of the night. Tender, succulent, and two pieces in an app just wasn't enough for the table (we wanted more!). Plus the veggies that accompanied each platter was on point. Only con at this visit was the egg on the fried chicken salad. It was hard boiled, which is not my typical go to for cooking eggs but just didn't compliment the salad. Otherwise every dish including the chicken salad was an absolute delight. Will definitely be back.

Fyi - This place is wine and beer only.</Review>

<name>spudhufer< /name>< time>
1407875810382<//time>
<Rating>5< /Rating><Text>Had the pleasure of checking out circa tonight with a friend. Between both of us we were able to sample about 70% of the small plates, 2 entrees, and 2 desserts.

My take .....

Owner / Chef Mike Almos has created a warm neighborhood restaurant serving locally sourced comfort food to a blues / Jazz soundtrack courtesy the restaurant's vinyl collection.

The interior is warm and relaxed, keeping some of the Farmhouse's accoutrements, like the table and chairs while adding its own identity and touches, like the reclaimed wood bar.

Local Craft beer plays a big part in the restaurant, not only making up the majority of the beverage program, but also being incorporated as an ingredient into quite a few of the restaurant's menu items .

What we ate...

Young Greens ~ locally grown butter leaf lettuce, poblano cornbread, goat cheese,
green tomato dressing with 'wall-greens' basil.

Home-brew Braised Bratwurst ~ house-made hopped brat, pale ale pan jus, sauerkraut, grain mustard.
this is a must order app.

Saut√©ed Baja White Shrimp ~ Tomato, basil leaves, house-made farmer's cheese, Belgian blonde broth.

Succotash & Brussels Sprouts ~ Sweet corn, brussel leaves, green beans, vegetable broth, maple glazed pork belly.

*OK we all know pork belly rocks but the succotash in this dish stole the show. Every vegetable was perfectly cooked and could be tasted distinctly while still working in unison with the dish.

Slow Cooked Pork Shoulder ~ Achiote marinade, plantains, yams, organic dates, herbed pan jus.

Chicken & Dumplings ~ Mary's chicken, Belgian blonde ale, root vegis, gold potatoes,sweet peas, fresh sage.

*A deceptively simple seeming dish loaded with flavor.

Banana Split ~ Bananas Foster, fresh berries, agave nectar,
spiced date vanilla bean ice cream

Berries & Cream ~ Fresh berries, fig balsamic syrup, pistachio ice cream, white cake.

*Oh and they make all their own ice cream.

If your down in University Heights or the area I would highly recommend stopping by Circa for elevated comfort food, made with top quality ingredients, executed right.

Even after our little hedonistic plunge we left not feeling bloated or stuffed because even though it was a lot of food it was not laden with salt and fat. Instead the flavor came from the product and the execution.

Someone else earlier complained about blandness, I disagree I had no problem picking up flavor and depth of flavor at that.</Text><Pics>None< /Pics><response>None</response>< gmap_id>
0x80d9551da49011df:0xfd9929fc5837b435</gmap_id>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Response>
None<//Response>

<text>First, these are very nice people, and with generally good intentions. This said, their business model is all about taking profit in my estimation, not the best interest of the customer.

They offered a $1,600 converter change price for a job that typically cost $800-$1,000. Additionally, they priced a converter at  $280, a part that typically costs $175 for my vehicle, and said it would take 3 days to ship from Salt Lake City. I checked the local Autozone which had the part in stock for $159. Or, they offered to change the fluid, pan gasket and filter for $446, a typically $150-$175 job. I took this option in hopes it would help me limp home.

<Time>1580517625992<//Time><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
A really fabulous experience for all lovers of Jelly Belly!

There is a free tour here which is informative, but self guided.  There is a large shop for purchasing all of your favorite Jelly Belly‚Äôs and a tasting bar as well!

There is a cafe and outdoor area where you can sit down and enjoy a bite to eat.

The factory also has a shop which makes fudge and chocolate as well.

All the things you need for your resident sugar overload!!!<//Text>

Love going here. I always see and learn something new. Best time to go is during the week so the kids can see the factory in process. Very inexpensive.<//text>

<Review>Had a free tour of the factory and learned about the process of making jelly beans. They have a sample bar for you to try out the different flavors of jelly beans, but you‚Äôre limited to 3 flavors at a time. They have a large variety of flavors so make sure you try as many as possible. The tour itself was self-guided and lasted about 15-20 minutes depending on how long you want to stay at some sections. There are games throughout the tour for kids to play. At the end of the tour, we were given 2 packs of jelly beans to take home for free.<//Review>< pictures>

Great place too take the kids! Very informative on the Jelly Bean process, I had no idea the time and precision it took to make the candy. It was also very patriotic about the great US president and California governor
Ronald Regan. A classic All American Company.<//review>

< Text>
Took the grandkids to the Jelly Belly factory as a surprise. Had a great time, did the fiery five challenge where you eat progressively hotter jelly beans from cayenne all the way to Carolina Reaper, I had to stop at habanero. You have to try the chocolate covered bacon and the fudge with bacon, surprisingly good. the artwork made out of jelly bellies is very cool! Can‚Äôt wait to go again!

Update: they also have paid guided tours actually in the factory, you get to wear a Jelly Belly uniform and be down on the factory floor.< /Text>

Jelly Belly is another tourist attraction that one should visit. It is roughly 1.5 hours drive from San Jose. This factory is so impressive as the production floor is so clean and organized. If you love sweet stuff, then you must visit this place as it is a family owned business for six generations. This is our second visits and every time our kids buy a lot of authentic Jelly beans with hundreds of different flavors.
We also love wine tasting for only $20 per person. I would recommend this place to everyone. The staffs are professional and friendly. You can also try samples for free.< /review>

< Text>
This is a great family activity especially if you are looking for something fun and cheap. The tour is completely free and great for all ages. My three year old loved it and yet it was interesting for me to. On top of that they give you a free jelly belly hat and some free jelly bellies too. The have a tasting area where you can taste as many beans as you want. They limit you to three beans at a time but you can go through as many times as you want.<//Text>

< Review>
Amazing experience to see some of my favorite candies being made.  Their tour is nice and informative including little games for children to play along the way.  The sample bar is incredible since I have never even know that they made more than jelly beans.  Staff was very friendly and the grounds were immaculately maintained.  There is even a game fire hydrant for four legged friends complete with a sign that states it's not a real hydrant.  There children loved it and so did I.< /Review>

< text>
Always Great deals! I didn't take the tour this time due to Covid 19 restrictions. They made a few changes to the layout to accommodate restrictions. You can only go in the front. The exit is the side by the cafe. Purchases are made in a one-way direction and spaced out for safety.  The fudge is not in view and you can no longer self-fill bags. Instead the bags are in 1/2 pound bags for $5 behind the counter. Due to spacing there's fewer purchase displays. Otherwise it was pretty much the same for me! I spent too much LOL</text>

<UserId.>115175275508805116327< /UserId.>< user_name>
Kimberly< /user_name>
<Time>1578838292686<//Time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< review>
My niece wanted something to do...so I brought her here.

It's a fun place to go. They offer free tours of the factory every 30 minutes.

During the tour they have televisions that tell you about the process of making the jelly beans and of the history.  Its incredible the amount of Jellybeans that are made.

As consumers..we just buy off the shelf..but to see the process is pretty cool.

Along the way the have made portraits of different presidents and Elvis out of Jellybeans.

At the end of the tour they give you small sample bags of candy...

This is free.

As you walk in they have a sampling counter with many flavors to choose from.  You can choose 3 to try.

In the store they sell merchandise..
Chocolates...Jellybeans...soda ect.

At the back they have a deli that sells burgers...fries ect just in case you get hungry while being here.

Across from this deli they have a clearance store where the items are marked down significantly.

They offer bags of candy for 75% off the original price which is awesome.

If you have never been here before..
It's a pretty neat place to see.

Dont forget to buy the dog food...fart...booger...dirty sock jelly beans to prank someone...ü§™ü§™ü§™ü§™ü§™<//review>

<userid>113622914447638190429</userid>< name>
Nathan Yang< /name>
<Time>1526771064713< /Time><rating>5<//rating><text>This place is a combination of Jelly Belly amusement park store and a self-guided tour of the factory. It should be quite fun for kids. Adults will probably not be particularly interested in the tour. You can walk through it in 10-20 minutes.

On the other hand, there's really nothing to complain about. The tour is free, and we received a free Jelly Belly sample bag at the end. The staff are also very kind.

For adults, there is a wine & chocolate tasting upstairs. In fact, it's the best $15 wine + chocolate tasting I've had. I'm not sure why there's a tasting room in the Jelly Belly Visitor Center, but I'm very glad it exists. Without it, our tour would've been rather dry.< /text><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOg8zMGMvNlwQajmxpm1p2gQHS_mRGqxw4iWpv-=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCj6YQlxV3cXOal8ZwB0JDZXxy8KaQkfTjqeXh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOSHpN5DxAoRT37Ide6kivAKoYELfu6TCy2zh4o=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNLhMSmtv0XNSfLnvt1oeDbT28yKvoSPs-74qjy=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pictures><Resp>{'time': 1526773800364, 'text': 'Nathan, thanks for your comments. <Time>1536178544435</Time><Text>Crowded!  Waiting in line for the free factory tour takes awhile.  We actually went upstairs to do a wine and chocolate tasting that also allowed us to skip the queue for the factory tour.  The wines were uninspired especially considering the proximity to Napa, but the chocolates were good (I did not realize Jelly Belly made chocolate.)  I am not a jelly bean fan but the tour was interesting.  Although next time I will pay for a guided tour and try to go when the factory is actually operating.  A bonus was we ran into the CEO of Jelly Belly during the tour!

Be prepared for limited parking on the weekends.

This is a fun and low cost thing to do.  And inexpensive but high quality chocolate can be found here!<//Text><user_name>Steven</user_name><GmapID>0x8085140b66039437:0x727fe552568827b2<//GmapID>< Rating>
4</Rating>

<Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPyEwQcBLVWd2r9qq-rAcOVX5Z84twahoC8AMr0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOwGM0dgb4viA7uh5j21eF6VGU7xFv_M2MPX7p3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNXoFVmnFcJl3keg09UqR-FIa0Tzj2JLr39Lait=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMVmS7ktwniji7CwUMturigT1IM1Cc5nDqe3xC8=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>< user_id>

<username>Steven</username><gmap_id>0x8085140b66039437:0x727fe552568827b2< /gmap_id>< Time>
1536178544435<//Time>
< rate>
4<//rate>
< Review>
Crowded!  Waiting in line for the free factory tour takes awhile.  We actually went upstairs to do a wine and chocolate tasting that also allowed us to skip the queue for the factory tour.  The wines were uninspired especially considering the proximity to Napa, but the chocolates were good (I did not realize Jelly Belly made chocolate.)  I am not a jelly bean fan but the tour was interesting.  Although next time I will pay for a guided tour and try to go when the factory is actually operating.  A bonus was we ran into the CEO of Jelly Belly during the tour!

Be prepared for limited parking on the weekends.

This is a fun and low cost thing to do.  And inexpensive but high quality chocolate can be found here!</Review>

<UserId.>102921602555056398853< /UserId.><user_name>Devin Fane< /user_name>< Date>
1570859629161<//Date>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Review>
I enjoyed the whole Jelly Belly experience. From walking to the front of the factory and taking pictures at the giant Jelly Belly sign to walking around the store trying to decide which and how many Jelly Bellys I was going to get. I thought that the tour was very informative and I got to see pretty much everything. I now know when the company started and how many generations of the family work together on it now. In addition to this now I know how they make the mold for the jelly beans, which is quite brilliant and cost effective. The tour is self-guided, and everything was relatively easy to navigate. This is a great place for people of all ages. The tour is also wheel chair accessible. Wonderful place, wonderful people, wonderful candy.<//Review>

< userid>
111767994861627815680< /userid>
< username>
SAL MARINO</username>
<date>1535408445718</date>< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
A must see when you are in Fairfield, CALIFORNIA, stop by and treat yourself on a live factory field trip during operational hours M-F (9 am - 4 pm). At the end of the plant tour, each tour participant gets a bag of Jelly Belly candy sample. The candy showroom has an eye-catching display of colorful Jelly Bean candies, be sure to go to the sample station and find out your favorite flavors. You can purchase an unlimited amount of Candies in the Showroom. There is even a Portrait of President Ronald Reagan made of Jelly Bean candies, this was his favorite candy, just so you know. The candy factory runs their very own fast food restaurant in case you get hungry. If you are in town, stop by for the experience, and you will not be disappointed.<//Review>

100313079482906781956< /user>
<name>Anna Leontine Ortiz< /name><Date>1565597982153<//Date><rate>4</rate>< Review>
Came here with my Meetup group. We were five adults, 3 children. We came knowing that production doesn't happen on weekends and that they have a self-paced video tour. I've been here before so I knew the general layout and everything but for the people visiting for the first time, it was easy for them to get to the gift shop and cafe. The prices for photos are still way too much money but I still love that they do them. I wish they'd offer a cheap digital only package. The Wine/Chocolate tasting was a nice addition from when I was last there. Three of the adults in our group participated and enjoyed themselves. They liked that it was pretty inexpensive. Overall we had a very good time. Highly recommend a trip here.< /Review>

<text>Check website for days factory is closed, or production is stopped. Tour runs daily from 8am to 4pm, every 10 to 15 minutes. Lots of free parking, enter main building to line up for the group tour. Groups enter to first watch a video, then tour plant on your own. Lots to learn, and see. Viewing windows for adults and kids. You can observe all aspects of jelly belly production. After tour there's a store, and food court. A must for kids. Free samples!<//text>< Pictures>

<Review>How you anyone NOT like this place! It's amazing. When we pop those Jelly Belly candy we never think twice about how their made. But once you take the free tour, you gain a deeper appreciation on all the effort it takes to make em.

This is one of those place that you definitely have to put on your bucket list. Fun environment and their cafeteria (I didn't eat here though) had some pretty cool pizza shaped like a Jelly Belly.

Their Jelly Belly store can be pretty dangerous.. it's very enticing and makes you want to buy everything. Being a factory store, it seems they had lot of unique flavors I didn't see in the supermarket.

It's also amazing they introduces some new bold flavors and quite frankly, it's not for me or the faint of heart. But the kids love them.. why anyone would want to eat Jelly Belly flavors like "rotten egg" or " dead fish" or "vomit" is beyond my small brain.<//Review><rating>5<//rating><Name>Eric Tam<//Name>< user>

<review>Check website for days factory is closed, or production is stopped. Tour runs daily from 8am to 4pm, every 10 to 15 minutes. Lots of free parking, enter main building to line up for the group tour. Groups enter to first watch a video, then tour plant on your own. Lots to learn, and see. Viewing windows for adults and kids. You can observe all aspects of jelly belly production. After tour there's a store, and food court. A must for kids. Free samples!< /review>< time>

<Rate>5<//Rate><review>How you anyone NOT like this place! It's amazing. When we pop those Jelly Belly candy we never think twice about how their made. But once you take the free tour, you gain a deeper appreciation on all the effort it takes to make em.

This is one of those place that you definitely have to put on your bucket list. Fun environment and their cafeteria (I didn't eat here though) had some pretty cool pizza shaped like a Jelly Belly.

Their Jelly Belly store can be pretty dangerous.. it's very enticing and makes you want to buy everything. Being a factory store, it seems they had lot of unique flavors I didn't see in the supermarket.

It's also amazing they introduces some new bold flavors and quite frankly, it's not for me or the faint of heart. But the kids love them.. why anyone would want to eat Jelly Belly flavors like "rotten egg" or " dead fish" or "vomit" is beyond my small brain.</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Resp>

<user>106226941420364887072<//user><Review>FREE Jelly beans!  FREE tour!! Free is good. I'm a fan. :)

Tours happen about every 15 minutes and the tour lasted about 45 minutes.  The tour was a cool experience - things typically aren't running during the weekends, so if you want to see the factory in action I recommend coming during the week.

I liked learning about Jelly Belly, but I wish that the tour relied less on video monitors and more on someone just talking us through the factory.  It definitely works from a scalability perspective so it makes tours efficient, but it was a little less special as a result.

Each year on the first Saturday of December, for nearly the past 2 decades, Jelly Belly has hosted inside the Visitor Center our annual Christmas party for the employees and their guests.   Unfortunately, we have to close early that day to prepare upstairs and downstairs for hundreds of employees and their guests.\n\nWe have this information written on our website and on our online calendar, as well as our 800 line (800-953-5592). The website doesn't doesn't mention that July is the slow season so they take this time to test, repair, and replace machines. It is still fun to see, they have videos that walk you through the tour and show you what the machines do, but only a few are actually running during this time. Don't let my review stop you from going, just be aware that the factory is not at full steam. <user_id>115566403968890647637</user_id>< Name>
Blaze Windrider</Name>
<date>1475870915206</date>< rating>
5< /rating>
< text>
Childhood dream of visiting this candy factory fulfilled.  It's a self-guided tour so you can move at your own pace and watch tiny jelly beans form from start to finish.

Once finished, their candy store awaits, plying the senses with a multitude of sights, smells and flavors to wander through.

If you've ever wondered what Buttered Popcorn flavored Fudge was like, this is the place to find out (PS: It's awesome).

I would recommend everyone, the young and old, all come and wander through. Learn a thing or two, then spike your bloodsugar for the next month with a visit to the Jelly Belly Factory.</text>

<rate>5< /rate>< Text>
The Jelly Belly is a family affair where we load up all the grandchildren and make our yearly trek for boxes of Jelly Bellys and other memorabilia. This week we go with six grandchildren ranging in ages from 3-18, and I know without a doubt that every one of us will have a great time. The "train ride" is interesting as well as informative and fun, and the gift shop is amazing for all ages so be sure to plan out some extra time for browsing. We have been making memories with Jelly Belly for years and absolutely love love the place. You can't go wrong bringing your family to the Jelly Belly Candy Company.< /Text>

<date>1468851598559<//date><Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
The Jelly Belly is a family affair where we load up all the grandchildren and make our yearly trek for boxes of Jelly Bellys and other memorabilia. This week we go with six grandchildren ranging in ages from 3-18, and I know without a doubt that every one of us will have a great time. The "train ride" is interesting as well as informative and fun, and the gift shop is amazing for all ages so be sure to plan out some extra time for browsing. We have been making memories with Jelly Belly for years and absolutely love love the place. You can't go wrong bringing your family to the Jelly Belly Candy Company.</text>

<review>I can't believe this is free. For no cost, you can take a self-guided tour of the factory. You walk on bridges overlooking the factory, as the TVs tell you about the history of Jelly Bellys, the process of making them, etc. You can also sample any of the hundreds of flavors. As you go through the line, you can only ask for 3 flavors, just for the sake of quickly getting through the line, but you can go through the line as many times as you want. You also get a free paper hat. Of course, there's also a store that sells everything they make.< /review>< Pics>

<Date>1432219584165< /Date><rate>3<//rate>< Review>
Love that they do tours here! It was really cool to walk through and see the whole process of making a jelly belly and learn some of the history of jelly belly as well. I wish more companies would do this.
The whole walk through area for the tour just looks dated.  Old dirty worn out carpet, and TV's and speakers that are old and often times not working. Not to mention it's loud as you walk through. So loud that it's hard to ask the tour guide questions while walking through.

Neat to see the process and I think it's worth doing once, but could definitely use an update.</Review>

<date>1432219584165</date><Rate>3<//Rate>< Review>
Love that they do tours here! It was really cool to walk through and see the whole process of making a jelly belly and learn some of the history of jelly belly as well. I wish more companies would do this.
The whole walk through area for the tour just looks dated.  Old dirty worn out carpet, and TV's and speakers that are old and often times not working. Not to mention it's loud as you walk through. So loud that it's hard to ask the tour guide questions while walking through.

Neat to see the process and I think it's worth doing once, but could definitely use an update.< /Review>

< user_id>
108476892568623540954<//user_id>
< username>
Mark Casey<//username>
<Time>1375924606316<//Time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< review>
This is a fantastic tour.  It's free.  Less than free, actually, as they give you a bag of jelly beans on the way out.  What you get for your less than free admission price is a really fun tour of the Jelly Belly factory.

The worst part of the tour is they way it starts with them taking a picture of your and your companions in front of a green screen that they later populate with images of jelly beans.  At the end of the tour you can purchase this for an absurdly high price or not bother.  They don't put any pressure on you, which is nice.

Then you get into the elevated walkway around the factory.  This is where the really cool part starts.  They show you the packaging and shipping lines, and if you like watching bag-filling machines and conveyor belts and Fanuc robots lifting boxes and trays of jelly bean trays -- and I do! -- this is totally fascinating.  As you walk around they show you other parts of the process, e.g. where the raw materials are stored, how the candy centers are made, how the outer layers are added, how the Jelly Belly logo is printed on, how they weed out the beans that are too large or small.

There is also a video segment on Ronald Reagan's love of Jelly Bellies.  And, there is an art gallery full of Jelly Belly mosaics.  Reagan fans will love this part of the tour.

Along the way they give you a small number of beans to sample.  And, our tour guide was legitimately funny.

At the end of the tour they dump you in a huge store full of their products.  The deformed beans -- Belly Flops -- are sold at great prices.  The other prices approximate what you'd pay in a Safeway.

This is a kid friendly tour that adults will like as well.  If you can, be sure to go on a weekday so you can see the plant in operation.< /review>

<user_name>Iama Techie< /user_name>< time>
1495336442966</time>
< pics>
None< /pics>
< text>
If you are at all whimsical, especially regarding jelly beans, you have to take a stop here and take the tour.
Give yourself at least 1 hour. They allow 60 people through at a time and, although it is a "self-guided" tour, you may find yourself watching all the videos on large screen TVs placed about every 50'-100' feet, explaining what is going on below. There are also some very nice employees at each of those to answer additional questions.
I was lucky enough to be near two employees, one new and the other explaining more detail and data about the goings on below. Really fascinating. And the aroma.. WOW!
After the tour, you're definitely going to want to pick up some kind of candy. I personally felt compelled "free" some of the poor rejected jellies, those that were too big or too small to be "just right". They call them "Belly Flops" and they are just as tasty as the "normal" beans. :-)
Lot's of gift ideas as well as other candy in the shop downstairs. There is also a cafeteria. But.. although the food I ordered was quite fresh and tasty, I thought a 12 minute wait for a simple 'breakfast burrito" was a little long. Still.. where else would you get Jelly Bean shaped burgers or pizza??
I also LOVE how they decorated everything up for Halloween. Such a fun place to work!

**NOTE: The Jelly Belly website says it's open from 8am, but it doesn't until 9am, and the tours don't start until 9:15.
Also.. right after the tour "begins" there is a photographer taking a picture of each tour group standing in front of a giant stuffed jelly bean. Unless you want to spend an additional $15, $20, $30 on a pretty unimaginative picture AND have to wait back in line while everyone gets their picture taken, I would ask to just move past it to the real excitement.
I wish I could take my kids here...
Definitely recommend!< /text>

< Review>
I love Jelly Belly, so many choices, some nasty,  like who likes vomit flavor? This was my first time here, crazy how long I've been in the bay area, and how I love the TRUE taste of every one!  My daughter, hubby, and my 2 Grandson's, surprised me! I loved the tour, very friendly staff made my experience exciting, a big kid in a candy store, indeed! Sunday, so no production lines in action, but there's lots of other fun... got to have fun smelling, and guessing which flavor it was, my favorite, buttered popcorn, and next is cotton candy, wait...I can't decide...so many great flavors... except the nasty ones...someone loves them! I was very amazed by the portraits, made with different colors, so realistic too! I also learned Ronald Regan ate black licorice flavor to help him stop smoking! I could go and tell much more, but I can't spoil it for others. Then we went to the best spot, The Store! Small, but Very well organized, and a wide selection of candy, toys, shirts, hats, and more, to please everyone, and you can sample lots of flavors, and YUMMY assorted FUDGE, wow! I only spent 20.00, and was able to get small gifts for my other 2 grandchildren, mommy, and dad too! Oh and of course me! I even got a cute retractable jelly belly headphone set for $6.99, for my daughter, as a thank you for a great experience! I really never thought of it being more than candy...it was a great learning experience! If you love jelly belly candy, it's the place to check out...free parking, free to take the tour, learn and see amazing artwork, kids of all ages will enjoy it! At the end of tour, the staff treats you to a FREE small bag of the 20 flavors, photos are taken with the big red jelly belly - at the entrance - ready at end of tour. We didn't buy ours, kind of expensive, and ours wasn't focused, probably due to squeezing all 5 of us in the shot, and it was a very quick "OK say cheese, not worth 25$ for 1 5√ó7 and 2 small wallets, but there's a little photo booth just before you exit, 3.00 for a strip, better deal! GO HAVE FUN, LEARN, SEE AMAZING BEAN ARTWORK, and more!< /Review>

(Translated by Google) Not just for kids!
An adorable jelly without! A must stop! When you enter the factory you can do an independent tour and see the entire production floor accompanied by digital explanations. Then they get photographed and get a gift under a jelly without. There is a souvenir shop and there is also a clearance shop on the side - where you sell things that came out of the store. A lovely factory and suitable for an hour and a half stop. do not miss.

(Translated by Google) Nice to see the production.

In retrospect, we saw the half-kilo package for $ 3.99 in the grocery outlet market.

It pays to be there early. So you still have your peace of mind and are safe from screaming children.

Ps: next to is also Budweiser;)
